-- Spanish Stocks: Santander, Telecinco, Acerinox, FCC Shares Move
-- B y   M a n u e l   B a i g o r r i
-- 2010-10-28T11:21:39Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-28/acerinox-banco-comercial-santander-iberian-equity-preview.html
Spain’s  IBEX 35 Index  was little
changed, adding 2.8, or less than 0.1 percent, to 10,702.9 at
1:21 p.m. in Madrid. The  Madrid Stock Exchange General Index  was
little changed, sliding less than 0.1 percent to 1,100.14.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
Spanish market. Symbols are in parentheses after company names.  Acerinox SA  (ACX SM) dropped 2.3 percent to 11.87 euros,
the stock’s fifth decline in six days and the IBEX 35 Index’s
worst performance today. The world’s biggest stainless-steel
maker posted a third-quarter net profit of 16.4 million euros
($22.7 million), missing the average analysts’ estimate of 33.6
million euros, according to a Bloomberg survey.  Banco Santander SA  (SAN SM) dropped for a fourth day,
losing 0.8 percent to 9.11 euros. The biggest Spanish bank
reported a 26 percent decline in third-quarter profit and said
it will miss its earnings goal for 2010 because of a Bank of
Spain rule forcing it to recognize bad loans earlier.  Fomento de Construcciones y Contratas SA  (FCC SM) rose 0.9
percent to 19.73 euros, the stock’s first increase in five days.
A group led by the Spanish company won a $1.45 billion contract
to build Panama City’s first metro line, FCC said.  Gestevision Telecinco SA  (TL5 SM) climbed 2.7 percent to
8.76 euros, the IBEX 35 Index’s best performance today. Spain’s
largest commercial TV station reported nine-month operating
profit and sales that beat analysts’ estimates on rising
advertising sales.  Telecinco’s earnings before interest and taxes doubled to
166.9 million euros, while revenue grew 44 percent to 622.4
million euros, the Madrid-based company said today in a
regulatory filing. The estimates by analysts in a Bloomberg
survey were for an operating profit of 148.3 million euros on
sales of 606.3 million euros.  Repsol YPF SA  (REP SM) advanced 1.6 percent to 19.75 euros,
erasing four days of losses. The Spanish oil company may boost
its dividend payment for next year by more than 10 percent, El
Economista reported, citing unidentified sources.  Viscofan SA  (VIS SM) rose 1.6 percent to 24.11 euros,
erasing the stock’s last two days of drops. The Spanish sausage-
casing maker’s nine-month profit climbed 28 percent to 61.2
million euros, it said in a filing to regulators today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
